text: Recent studies indicate that the tetracycline group of antibiotics is divisible into two classes on the basis of their modes of action (12). One class, the classical or typical tetracyclines, which includes compounds such as tetracy- cline, chlortetracycline, minocycline, and doxycycline, are bacteriostatic agents which enter the cell and prevent protein synthesis by interaction with the bacterial ribosome. The second class, or atypical tetracyclines, which includes com- pounds such as anhydrotetracycline, anhydrochlortetracy- cline, 6-thiatetracycline, chelocardin, and 4-epi-anhydro- chlortetracycline, do not directly inhibit protein synthesis and may prevent growth by interaction with the cell surface. There are two well-characterized mechanisms of bacterial resistance to typical tetracyclines, one of which involves efflux of antibiotic from the cell (illustrated by the Tet B determinant in Escherichia coli and the Tet K determinant in Staphylococcus aureus) and the other of which involves ribosomal protection (illustrated by Tet M) (14). Since the modes of action of atypical tetracyclines appear to differ fundamentally from those of other members of this antibiotic class, it was of interest to determine whether mechanisms of resistance to typical tetracyclines also confer protection against atypical tetracyclines. MICs of various tetracyclines for a set of E. coli and S. aureus strains were determined. For E. coli strains, MIC determinations were performed in M63 minimal medium (10) and brain heart infusion broth (5), whereas S. aureus strains were cultured only in brain heart medium. MICs were determined by a microtiter plate method by using 0.1 ml of growth medium per well, an inoculum density of 1 x 105 to 5 x 105 CFU/ml, and a range of antibiotic concentrations. Plates were incubated for 18 h at 35°C in a forced-air incubator, and the MICs were determined. The MIC was defined as the lowest concentration of antibiotic that inhibited growth of the organism. By dividing the MIC for a resistant strain by that for its susceptible parent, the relative level of resistance conferred by a partic- ular determinant was calculated (Table 2). In contrast to the results obtained with tetracycline, chlortetracycline, and minocycline, the susceptibility ratios obtained with atypical agents were always c 16, and in many cases, they were 1 to 2 (Table 2). The results show that the Tet B and Tet M determinants in E. coli offer little or no protection from atypical tetracyclines. The S. aureus Tet K determinant mediated high-level resistance to tetracycline and chlortetracycline but not to minocycline (Table 2). The failure of Tet K to encode resistance to minocycline is consistent with previously pub- lished data (1). In S. aureus, neither Tet K or Tet M conferred substantial resistance to the atypical tetracyclines, since susceptibility ratios of 8 or less were observed (Table 2).

Atypical tetracyclines appear to prevent bacterial growth as a consequence of an interaction with the cytoplasmic membrane (12). In view of this, tetracycline resistance mechanisms that operate at the level of the ribosome (Tet M) (14) or that remove antibiotic from the cytoplasm (Tet B, Tet K) (14) are not expected to confer resistance to atypical tetracyclines. The data presented here (Table 2) support these suggestions and confirm earlier reports that 6-thiatetracycline and chelocardin are active against tetra- cycline-resistant organisms (2, 15).
